# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: polka-node
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:polka-node/javascript] Web browsers have a dedicated JavaScript engine that executes the client code.
[src:polka-node/javascript] These engines are also utilized in some servers and a variety of apps.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The most popular runtime system for non-browser usage is Node.js.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript is a high-level, often just-in-time–compiled language that conforms to the ECMAScript standard.
[src:polka-node/javascript] It has dynamic typing, prototype-based object-orientation, and first-class functions.
[src:polka-node/javascript] It is multi-paradigm, supporting event-driven, functional, and imperative programming styles.
[src:polka-node/javascript] It has application programming interfaces (APIs) for working with text, dates, regular expressions, standard data structures, and the Document Object Model (DOM).
[src:polka-node/javascript] The ECMAScript standard does not include any input/output (I/O), such as networking, storage, or graphics facilities.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In practice, the web browser or other runtime system provides JavaScript APIs for I/O.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Although Java and JavaScript are similar in name and syntax, the two languages are distinct and differ greatly in design.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The first popular web browser with a graphical user interface, Mosaic, was released in 1993.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The lead developers of Mosaic then founded the Netscape corporation, which released a more polished browser, Netscape Navigator, in 1994.
[src:polka-node/javascript] During these formative years of the Web, web pages could only be static, lacking the capability for dynamic behavior after the page was loaded in the browser.
[src:polka-node/javascript] There was a desire in the flourishing web development scene to remove this limitation, so in 1995, Netscape decided to add a programming language to Navigator.
[src:polka-node/javascript] They pursued two routes to achieve this: collaborating with Sun Microsystems to embed the Java language, while also hiring Brendan Eich to embed the Scheme language.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The goal was a "language for the masses", "to help nonprogrammers create dynamic, interactive Web sites".
[src:polka-node/javascript] Netscape management soon decided that the best option was for Eich to devise a new language, with syntax similar to Java and less like Scheme or other extant scripting languages.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Although the new language and its interpreter implementation were called LiveScript when first shipped as part of a Navigator beta in September 1995, the name was changed to JavaScript for the official release in December.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The choice of the *JavaScript* name has caused confusion, implying that it is directly related to Java.
[src:polka-node/javascript] At the time, the dot-com boom had begun and Java was a popular new language, so Eich considered the JavaScript name a marketing ploy by Netscape.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Microsoft debuted Internet Explorer in 1995, leading to a browser war with Netscape.
[src:polka-node/javascript] On the JavaScript front, Microsoft created its own interpreter called JScript.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Microsoft first released JScript in 1996, alongside initial support for CSS and extensions to HTML.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Each of these implementations was noticeably different from their counterparts in Netscape Navigator.
[src:polka-node/javascript] These differences made it difficult for developers to make their websites work well in both browsers, leading to widespread use of "best viewed in Netscape" and "best viewed in Internet Explorer" logos for several years.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In November 1996, Netscape submitted JavaScript to Ecma International, as the starting point for a standard specification that all browser vendors could conform to.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This led to the official release of the first ECMAScript language specification in June 1997.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The standards process continued for a few years, with the release of ECMAScript 2 in June 1998 and ECMAScript 3 in December 1999.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, the effort to fully standardize the language was undermined by Microsoft gaining an increasingly dominant position in the browser market.
[src:polka-node/javascript] By the early 2000s, Internet Explorer's market share reached 95%.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This meant that JScript became the de facto standard for client-side scripting on the Web.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Microsoft initially participated in the standards process and implemented some proposals in its JScript language, but eventually it stopped collaborating on ECMA work.
[src:polka-node/javascript] During the period of Internet Explorer dominance in the early 2000s, client-side scripting was stagnant.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This started to change in 2004, when the successor of Netscape, Mozilla, released the Firefox browser.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Firefox was well received by many, taking significant market share from Internet Explorer.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In 2005, Mozilla joined ECMA International, and work started on the ECMAScript for XML (E4X) standard.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This led to Mozilla working jointly with Macromedia (later acquired by Adobe Systems), who were implementing E4X in their ActionScript 3 language, which was based on an ECMAScript 4 draft.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The goal became standardizing ActionScript 3 as the new ECMAScript 4.
[src:polka-node/javascript] To this end, Adobe Systems released the Tamarin implementation as an open source project.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, Tamarin and ActionScript 3 were too different from established client-side scripting, and without cooperation from Microsoft, ECMAScript 4 never reached fruition.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Meanwhile, very important developments were occurring in open-source communities not affiliated with ECMA work.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In 2005, Jesse James Garrett released a white paper in which he coined the term Ajax and described a set of technologies, of which JavaScript was the backbone, to create web applications where data can be loaded in the background, avoiding the need for full page reloads.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This sparked a renaissance period of JavaScript, spearheaded by open-source libraries and the communities that formed around them.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Many new libraries were created, including jQuery, Prototype, Dojo Toolkit, and MooTools.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Google debuted its Chrome browser in 2008, with the V8 JavaScript engine that was faster than its competition.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The key innovation was just-in-time compilation (JIT), so other browser vendors needed to overhaul their engines for JIT.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In July 2008, these disparate parties came together for a conference in Oslo.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This led to the eventual agreement in early 2009 to combine all relevant work and drive the language forward.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The result was the ECMAScript 5 standard, released in December 2009.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Ambitious work on the language continued for several years, culminating in an extensive collection of additions and refinements being formalized with the publication of ECMAScript 6 in 2015.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The creation of Node.js in 2009 by Ryan Dahl sparked a significant increase in the usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Node combines the V8 engine, an event loop, and I/O APIs, thereby providing a stand-alone JavaScript runtime system.
[src:polka-node/javascript] As of 2018, Node had been used by millions of developers, and npm had the most modules of any package manager in the world.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The ECMAScript draft specification is currently maintained openly on GitHub, and editions are produced via regular annual snapshots.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Potential revisions to the language are vetted through a comprehensive proposal process.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Now, instead of edition numbers, developers check the status of upcoming features individually.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The current JavaScript ecosystem has many libraries and frameworks, established programming practices, and substantial usage of JavaScript outside of web browsers.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Plus, with the rise of single-page applications and other JavaScript-heavy websites, several transpilers have been created to aid the development process.
[src:polka-node/javascript] As of 2025, the overwhelming majority of websites (98.9%) use JavaScript for client side webpage behavior.
[src:polka-node/javascript] "JavaScript" is a trademark of Oracle Corporation in the United States.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The trademark was originally issued to Sun Microsystems on 6 May 1997, and was transferred to Oracle when they acquired Sun in 2009.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A letter was circulated in September 2024, spearheaded by Ryan Dahl, calling on Oracle to free the JavaScript trademark.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Brendan Eich, the original creator of JavaScript, was among the over 14,000 signatories who supported the initiative.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript is the dominant client-side scripting language of the Web, with 99% of all websites using it for this purpose.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Scripts are embedded in or included from HTML documents and interact with the DOM.
[src:polka-node/javascript] All major web browsers have a built-in JavaScript engine that executes the code on the user's device.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Over 80% of websites use a third-party JavaScript library or web framework as part of their client-side scripting.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Other notable ones include Angular, Bootstrap, Lodash, Modernizr, React, Underscore, and Vue.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Multiple options can be used in conjunction, such as jQuery and Bootstrap.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, the term "Vanilla JS" was coined for websites not using any libraries or frameworks at all, instead relying entirely on standard JavaScript functionality.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The use of JavaScript has expanded beyond its web browser roots.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript engines are now embedded in a variety of other software systems, both for server-side website deployments and non-browser applications.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Initial attempts at promoting server-side JavaScript usage were Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's Internet Information Services, but they were small niches.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Server-side usage eventually started to grow in the late 2000s, with the creation of Node.js and other approaches.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Electron, Cordova, React Native, and other application frameworks have been used to create many applications with behavior implemented in JavaScript.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Other non-browser applications include Adobe Acrobat support for scripting PDF documents and GNOME Shell extensions written in JavaScript.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Oracle used to provide Nashorn, a JavaScript interpreter, as part of their Java Development Kit (JDK) API library along with **jjs** a command line interpreter as of JDK version 8.
[src:polka-node/javascript] As a replacement Oracle offered GraalJS which can also be used with the OpenJDK which allows one to create and reference Java objects in JavaScript code and add runtime scripting in JavaScript to applications written in Java.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript has been used in some embedded systems, usually by leveraging Node.js.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The first JavaScript engines were interpreters of the source code, but modern engines use just-in-time compilation to improve performance.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript engines are typically developed by web browser vendors, and every major browser includes one.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In a browser, the JavaScript engine runs in concert with the rendering engine via the Document Object Model and Web IDL bindings.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, the use of JavaScript engines is not limited to browsers; For example, the V8 engine is a core component of the Node.js runtime system.
[src:polka-node/javascript] They are also called ECMAScript engines, after the official name of the specification.
[src:polka-node/javascript] With the advent of WebAssembly, some engines can also execute this code in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A JavaScript engine must be embedded within a runtime system (such as a web browser or a standalone system) to enable scripts to interact with the broader environment.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The runtime system includes the necessary APIs for input/output operations, such as networking, storage, and graphics, and provides the ability to import scripts.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript is a single-threaded language.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The runtime processes messages from a queue one at a time, and it calls a function associated with each new message, creating a call stack frame with the function's arguments and local variables.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The call stack shrinks and grows based on the function's needs.
[src:polka-node/javascript] When the call stack is empty upon function completion, JavaScript proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This is called the event loop, described as "run to completion" because each message is fully processed before the next message is considered.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, the language's concurrency model describes the event loop as non-blocking: program I/O is performed using events and callback functions.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This means, for example, that JavaScript can process a mouse click while waiting for a database query to return information.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The notable standalone runtimes are Node.js, Deno, and Bun.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The following features are common to all conforming ECMAScript implementations unless explicitly specified otherwise.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The number of cited reserved words including keywords is 50–60 and varies depending on the implementation.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript supports much of the structured programming syntax from C (e.g., `if` statements, `while` loops, `switch` statements, `do while` loops, etc.).
[src:polka-node/javascript] One partial exception is scoping: originally JavaScript only had function scoping with `var`; block scoping was added in ECMAScript 2015 with the keywords `let` and `const`.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Like C, JavaScript makes a distinction between expressions and statements.
[src:polka-node/javascript] One syntactic difference from C is automatic semicolon insertion, which allow semicolons (which terminate statements) to be omitted.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript is weakly typed, which means certain types are implicitly cast depending on the operation used.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Values are cast to numbers by casting to strings and then casting the strings to numbers.
[src:polka-node/javascript] These processes can be modified by defining `toString` and `valueOf` functions on the prototype for string and number casting respectively.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript has received criticism for the way it implements these conversions as the complexity of the rules can be mistaken for inconsistency.
[src:polka-node/javascript] For example, when adding a number to a string, the number will be cast to a string before performing concatenation, but when subtracting a number from a string, the string is cast to a number before performing subtraction.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Often also mentioned is `{} + []` resulting in `0` (number).
[src:polka-node/javascript] This is misleading: the `{}` is interpreted as an empty code block instead of an empty object, and the empty array is cast to a number by the remaining unary `+` operator.
[src:polka-node/javascript] If the expression is wrapped in parentheses - `({} + [])` – the curly brackets are interpreted as an empty object and the result of the expression is `"[object Object]"` as expected.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript is dynamically typed like most other scripting languages.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A type is associated with a value rather than an expression.
[src:polka-node/javascript] For example, a variable initially bound to a number may be reassigned to a string.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript supports various ways to test the type of objects, including duck typing.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript includes an `eval` function that can execute statements provided as strings at run-time.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In JavaScript, an object is an associative array, augmented with a prototype (see below); each key provides the name for an object property, and there are two syntactical ways to specify such a name: dot notation (`obj.x = 10`) and bracket notation (`obj["x"] = 10`).
[src:polka-node/javascript] A property may be added, rebound, or deleted at run-time.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Most properties of an object (and any property that belongs to an object's prototype inheritance chain) can be enumerated using a `for...in` loop.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript uses prototypes where many other object-oriented languages use classes for inheritance, but it's still possible to simulate most class-based features with the prototype system.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Additionally, ECMAScript version 6 (released June 2015) introduced the keywords **class**, **extends** and **super**, which serve as syntactic sugar to abstract the underlying prototypal inheritance system with a more conventional interface.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Constructors are declared by specifying a method named **constructor**, and all classes are automatically subclasses of the base class Object, similarly to Java.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Though the underlying object mechanism is still based on prototypes, the newer syntax is similar to other object oriented languages.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Private variables are declared by prefixing the field name with a number sign (#), and polymorphism is not directly supported, although it can be emulated by manually calling different functions depending on the number and type of arguments provided.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Functions double as object constructors, along with their typical role.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Prefixing a function call with *new* will create an instance of a prototype, inheriting properties and methods from the constructor (including properties from the `Object` prototype).
[src:polka-node/javascript] ECMAScript 5 offers the `Object.create` method, allowing explicit creation of an instance without automatically inheriting from the `Object` prototype (older environments can assign the prototype to `null`).
[src:polka-node/javascript] The constructor's `prototype` property determines the object used for the new object's internal prototype.
[src:polka-node/javascript] New methods can be added by modifying the prototype of the function used as a constructor.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript's built-in classes, such as `Array` and `Object`, also have prototypes that can be modified.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, it's generally considered bad practice to modify built-in objects, because third-party code may use or inherit methods and properties from these objects, and may not expect the prototype to be modified.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Unlike in many object-oriented languages, in JavaScript there is no distinction between a function definition and a method definition.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Rather, the distinction occurs during function calling.
[src:polka-node/javascript] When a function is called as a method of an object, the function's local *this* keyword is bound to that object for that invocation.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript functions are first-class; a function is considered to be an object.
[src:polka-node/javascript] As such, a function may have properties and methods, such as `.call()` and `.bind()`.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A *nested* function is a function defined within another function.
[src:polka-node/javascript] It is created each time the outer function is invoked.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In addition, each nested function forms a lexical closure: the lexical scope of the outer function (including any constant, local variable, or argument value) becomes part of the internal state of each inner function object, even after execution of the outer function concludes.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript also supports anonymous functions.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript supports implicit and explicit delegation.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript natively supports various function-based implementations of Role patterns like Traits and Mixins.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Such a function defines additional behavior by at least one method bound to the `this` keyword within its `function` body.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A Role then has to be delegated explicitly via `call` or `apply` to objects that need to feature additional behavior that is not shared via the prototype chain.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Whereas explicit function-based delegation does cover composition in JavaScript, implicit delegation already happens every time the prototype chain is walked in order to, e.g., find a method that might be related to but is not directly owned by an object.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Once the method is found it gets called within this object's context.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Thus inheritance in JavaScript is covered by a delegation automatism that is bound to the prototype property of constructor functions.
[src:polka-node/javascript] An indefinite number of parameters can be passed to a function.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The function can access them through formal parameters and also through the local `arguments` object.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Variadic functions can also be created by using the `bind` method.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Like in many scripting languages, arrays and objects (associative arrays in other languages) can each be created with a succinct shortcut syntax.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In fact, these literals form the basis of the JSON data format.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript supports regular expressions for text searches and manipulation.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A built-in Promise object provides functionality for handling promises and associating handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual result.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript supplies combinator methods, which allow developers to combine multiple JavaScript promises and do operations based on different scenarios.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The methods introduced are: Promise.race, Promise.all, Promise.allSettled and Promise.any.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Async/await allows an asynchronous, non-blocking function to be structured in a way similar to an ordinary synchronous function.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Asynchronous, non-blocking code can be written, with minimal overhead, structured similarly to traditional synchronous, blocking code.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Variables in JavaScript can be defined using either the `var`, `let` or `const` keywords.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Variables defined without keywords will be defined at the global scope.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Arrow functions were first introduced in 6th Edition – ECMAScript 2015.
[src:polka-node/javascript] They shorten the syntax for writing functions in JavaScript.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Arrow functions are anonymous, so a variable is needed to refer to them in order to invoke them after their creation, unless surrounded by parenthesis and executed immediately.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Here is an example of JavaScript syntax.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Note the comments in the examples above, all of which were preceded with two forward slashes.
[src:polka-node/javascript] More examples can be found at the Wikibooks page on JavaScript syntax examples.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript and the DOM provide the potential for malicious authors to deliver scripts to run on a client computer via the Web.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Browser authors minimize this risk using two restrictions.
[src:polka-node/javascript] First, scripts run in a sandbox in which they can only perform Web-related actions, not general-purpose programming tasks like creating files.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Second, scripts are constrained by the same-origin policy: scripts from one website do not have access to information such as usernames, passwords, or cookies sent to another site.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Most JavaScript-related security bugs are breaches of either the same origin policy or the sandbox.
[src:polka-node/javascript] There are subsets of general JavaScript—ADsafe, Secure ECMAScript (SES)—that provide greater levels of security, especially on code created by third parties (such as advertisements).
[src:polka-node/javascript] Closure Toolkit is another project for safe embedding and isolation of third-party JavaScript and HTML.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Content Security Policy is the main intended method of ensuring that only trusted code is executed on a Web page.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A common JavaScript-related security problem is cross-site scripting (XSS), a violation of the same-origin policy.
[src:polka-node/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker can cause a target Website, such as an online banking website, to include a malicious script in the webpage presented to a victim.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The script in this example can then access the banking application with the privileges of the victim, potentially disclosing secret information or transferring money without the victim's authorization.
[src:polka-node/javascript] One important solution to XSS vulnerabilities is HTML sanitization.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Some browsers include partial protection against *reflected* XSS attacks, in which the attacker provides a URL including malicious script.
[src:polka-node/javascript] However, even users of those browsers are vulnerable to other XSS attacks, such as those where the malicious code is stored in a database.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Only correct design of Web applications on the server-side can fully prevent XSS.
[src:polka-node/javascript] XSS vulnerabilities can also occur because of implementation mistakes by browser authors.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Another cross-site vulnerability is cross-site request forgery (CSRF).
[src:polka-node/javascript] In CSRF, code on an attacker's site tricks the victim's browser into taking actions the user did not intend at a target site (like transferring money at a bank).
[src:polka-node/javascript] When target sites rely solely on cookies for request authentication, requests originating from code on the attacker's site can carry the same valid login credentials of the initiating user.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In general, the solution to CSRF is to require an authentication value in a hidden form field, and not only in the cookies, to authenticate any request that might have lasting effects.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Checking the HTTP Referrer header can also help.
[src:polka-node/javascript] "JavaScript hijacking" is a type of CSRF attack in which a `<script>` tag on an attacker's site exploits a page on the victim's site that returns private information such as JSON or JavaScript.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Developers of client-server applications must recognize that untrusted clients may be under the control of attackers.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The author of an application should not assume that their JavaScript code will run as intended (or at all) because any secret embedded in the code could be extracted by a determined adversary.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Package management systems such as npm and Bower are popular with JavaScript developers.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Such systems allow a developer to easily manage their program's dependencies upon other developers' program libraries.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Developers trust that the maintainers of the libraries will keep them secure and up to date, but that is not always the case.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A vulnerability has emerged because of this blind trust.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Relied-upon libraries can have new releases that cause bugs or vulnerabilities to appear in all programs that rely upon the libraries.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Inversely, a library can go unpatched with known vulnerabilities out in the wild.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In a study done looking over a sample of 133,000 websites, researchers found 37% of the websites included a library with at least one known vulnerability.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This occurred in March 2016 when Azer Koçulu removed his repository from npm.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This caused tens of thousands of programs and websites depending upon his libraries to break.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JavaScript provides an interface to a wide range of browser capabilities, some of which may have flaws such as buffer overflows.
[src:polka-node/javascript] These flaws can allow attackers to write scripts that would run any code they wish on the user's system.
[src:polka-node/javascript] This code is not by any means limited to another JavaScript application.
[src:polka-node/javascript] For example, a buffer overrun exploit can allow an attacker to gain access to the operating system's API with superuser privileges.
[src:polka-node/javascript] These flaws have affected major browsers including Firefox, Internet Explorer, and Safari.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Plugins, such as video players, Adobe Flash, and the wide range of ActiveX controls enabled by default in Microsoft Internet Explorer, may also have flaws exploitable via JavaScript (such flaws have been exploited in the past).
[src:polka-node/javascript] In Windows Vista, Microsoft has attempted to contain the risks of bugs such as buffer overflows by running the Internet Explorer process with limited privileges.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Google Chrome similarly confines its page renderers to their own "sandbox".
[src:polka-node/javascript] Web browsers are capable of running JavaScript outside the sandbox, with the privileges necessary to, for example, create or delete files.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Such privileges are not intended to be granted to code from the Web.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Incorrectly granting privileges to JavaScript from the Web has played a role in vulnerabilities in both Internet Explorer and Firefox.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In Windows XP Service Pack 2, Microsoft demoted JScript's privileges in Internet Explorer.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Microsoft Windows allows JavaScript source files on a computer's hard drive to be launched as general-purpose, non-sandboxed programs (see: Windows Script Host).
[src:polka-node/javascript] This makes JavaScript (like VBScript) a theoretically viable vector for a Trojan horse, although JavaScript Trojan horses are uncommon in practice.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In 2015, a JavaScript-based proof-of-concept implementation of a rowhammer attack was described in a paper by security researchers.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In 2017, a JavaScript-based attack via browser was demonstrated that could bypass ASLR.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In 2018, the paper that announced the Spectre attacks against Speculative Execution in Intel and other processors included a JavaScript implementation.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Important tools have evolved with the language.
[src:polka-node/javascript] A common misconception is that JavaScript is directly related to Java.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Both indeed have a C-like syntax (the C language being their most immediate common ancestor language).
[src:polka-node/javascript] They are also typically sandboxed, and JavaScript was designed with Java's syntax and standard library in mind.
[src:polka-node/javascript] In particular, all Java keywords were reserved in original JavaScript, JavaScript's standard library follows Java's naming conventions, and JavaScript's `Math` and `Date` objects are based on classes from Java 1.0.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Both languages first appeared in 1995, but Java was developed by James Gosling of Sun Microsystems and JavaScript by Brendan Eich of Netscape Communications.
[src:polka-node/javascript] The differences between the two languages are more prominent than their similarities.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Java has static typing, while JavaScript's typing is dynamic.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Java is loaded from compiled bytecode, while JavaScript is loaded as human-readable source code.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Java's objects are class-based, while JavaScript's are prototype-based.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Finally, Java did not support functional programming until Java 8, while JavaScript has done so from the beginning, being influenced by Scheme.
[src:polka-node/javascript] JSON is a data format derived from JavaScript; hence the name JavaScript Object Notation.
[src:polka-node/javascript] It is a widely used format supported by many other programming languages.
[src:polka-node/javascript] Many websites are JavaScript-heavy, so transpilers have been created to convert code written in other languages, which can aid the development process.
[src:polka-node/javascript] TypeScript and CoffeeScript are two notable languages that transpile to JavaScript.
[src:polka-node/javascript] WebAssembly is a newer language with a bytecode format designed to complement JavaScript, especially the performance-critical portions of web page scripts.
[src:polka-node/javascript] All of the major JavaScript engines support WebAssembly, which runs in the same sandbox as regular JavaScript code.
[src:polka-node/javascript] asm.js is a subset of JavaScript that served as the forerunner of WebAssembly.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Polka is an extremely minimal, highly performant Express.js alternative.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Yes, you're right, Express is *already* super fast & not *that* big 🤔 — but Polka shows that there was (somehow) room for improvement!
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Essentially, Polka is just a native HTTP server with added support for routing, middleware, and sub-applications.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Polka extends Trouter which means it inherits its API, too!
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] A custom, instantiated server that the Polka instance should attach its `handler` to.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] This is useful if you have initialized a server elsewhere in your application and want Polka to use *it* instead of creating a new `http.Server`.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Polka *only* updates the server when `polka.listen` is called.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] At this time, Polka will create a `http.Server` if a server was not already provided via `options.server`.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] A catch-all error handler; executed whenever a middleware throws an error.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Change this if you don't like default behavior.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Its signature is `(err, req, res, next)`, where `err` is the `String` or `Error` thrown by your middleware.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] A handler when no route definitions were matched.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Change this if you don't like default behavior, which sends a `404` status & `Not found` response.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Its signature is `(req, res)` and requires that you terminate the response.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Attach middleware(s) and/or sub-application(s) to the server.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] These will execute *before* your routes' handlers.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] The base path on which the following middleware(s) or sub-application should be mounted.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] You may pass one or more functions at a time.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Each function must have the standardized `(req, res, next)` signature.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] You may also pass a sub-application, which *must* be accompanied by a `base` pathname.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Please see `Middleware` and Express' middleware examples for more info.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] As of `v0.5.0`, this is an alias of the `@polka/url` module.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] For nearly all cases, you'll notice no changes.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Boots (or creates) the underlying `http.Server` for the first time.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] All arguments are passed to `server.listen` directly with no changes.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] As of `v0.5.0`, this method no longer returns a Promise.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Instead, the current Polka instance is returned directly, allowing for chained operations.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] The main Polka `IncomingMessage` handler.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] It receives all requests and tries to match the incoming URL against known routes.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] If the `req.url` is not immediately matched, Polka will look for sub-applications or middleware groups matching the `req.url`'s `base` path.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] If any are found, they are appended to the loop, running *after* any global middleware.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] At the end of the loop, if a middleware hasn't yet terminated the response (or thrown an error), the route handler will be executed, if found — otherwise a `(404) Not found` response is returned, configurable via `options.onNoMatch`.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Useful if you've already parsed the incoming path.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Otherwise, `app.parse` (aka `parseurl`) will run by default.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Routes are used to define how an application responds to varying HTTP methods and endpoints.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Each route is comprised of a path pattern, a HTTP method, and a handler (aka, what you want to do).
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Also, a single pathname (or `pattern`) may be reused with multiple METHODs.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] The following example demonstrates some simple routes.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Unlike the very popular `path-to-regexp`, Polka uses string comparison to locate route matches.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] While faster & more memory efficient, this does also prevent complex pattern matching.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] However, have no fear! 💥 All the basic and most commonly used patterns are supported.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Any named parameters included within your route `pattern` will be automatically added to your incoming `req` object.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] All parameters will be found within `req.params` under the same name they were given.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] However, only the most common methods are used throughout this documentation for demo purposes.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Request handlers accept the incoming `IncomingMessage` and the formulating `ServerResponse`.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Every route definition must contain a valid `handler` function, or else an error will be thrown at runtime.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] It's a **very good** practice to *always* terminate your response (`res.end`) inside a handler, even if you expect a middleware to do it for you.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] In the event a response is/was not terminated, the server will hang & eventually exit with a `TIMEOUT` error.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] No special preparation is needed — simply add the appropriate keywords.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Middleware are functions that run in between (hence "middle") receiving the request & executing your route's `handler` response.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] The middleware signature receives the request (`req`), the response (`res`), and a callback (`next`).
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] These can apply mutations to the `req` and `res` objects, and unlike Express, have access to `req.params`, `req.path`, `req.search`, and `req.query`!
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Most importantly, a middleware ***must*** either call `next()` or terminate the response (`res.end`).
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Failure to do this will result in a never-ending response, which will eventually crash the `http.Server`.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] In Polka, middleware functions are organized into tiers.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Unlike Express, Polka middleware are tiered into "global", "filtered", and "route-specific" groups.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Once the chain of middleware handler(s) has been composed, Polka will iterate through them sequentially until all functions have run, until a chain member has terminated the response early, or until a chain member has thrown an error.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Contrast this with Express, which does not tier your middleware and instead iterates through your entire application in the sequence that you composed it.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] If an error arises within a middleware, the loop will be exited.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] This means that no other middleware will execute & neither will the route handler.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Similarly, regardless of `statusCode`, an early response termination will also exit the loop & prevent the route handler from running.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] There are three ways to "throw" an error from within a middleware function.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] **Terminate the response early** Once the response has been ended, there's no reason to continue the loop!
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Quick comparison between various frameworks using `wrk` on `Node v10.4.0`.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Additional benchmarks between Polka and Express (using various Node versions) can be found here.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] Polka's API aims to be *very* similar to Express since most Node.js developers are already familiar with it.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] There are, however, a few main differences.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] **Any built-in view/rendering engines.** Most templating engines can be incorporated into middleware functions or used directly within a route handler.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] **The ability to `throw` from within middleware.** However, all other forms of middleware-errors are supported.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] (#14)** Express has a nice set of response helpers.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] While Polka relies on the native Node.js response methods, it would be very easy/possible to attach a global middleware that contained a similar set of helpers.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] **`RegExp`-based route patterns.** Polka's router uses string comparison to match paths against patterns.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] **Polka instances are not (directly) the request handler.** Most packages in the Express ecosystem expect you to pass your `app` directly into the package.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] This is because `express()` returns a middleware signature directly.
[src:polka-node/lukeed-polka] In the Polka-sphere, this functionality lives in your application's `handler` instead.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware often enables interoperability between applications that run on different operating systems, by supplying services so the application can exchange data in a standards-based way.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware sits "in the middle" between application software that may be working on different operating systems.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] It is similar to the middle layer of a three-tier single system architecture, except that it is stretched across multiple systems or applications.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Examples include EAI software, telecommunications software, transaction monitors, and messaging-and-queueing software.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] The distinction between operating system and middleware functionality is, to some extent, arbitrary.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] While core kernel functionality can only be provided by the operating system itself, some functionality previously provided by separately sold middleware is now integrated in operating systems.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] A typical example is the TCP/IP stack for telecommunications, nowadays included virtually in every operating system.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware is defined as software that provides a link between separate software applications.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] It is sometimes referred to as plumbing because it connects two applications and passes data between them.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware allows data contained in one database to be accessed through another.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] This makes it particularly useful for enterprise application integration and data integration tasks.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware gained popularity in the 1980s as a solution to the problem of how to link newer applications to older legacy systems, although the term had been in use since 1968.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] It also facilitated distributed processing, the connection of multiple applications to create a larger application, usually over a network.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] when compared to the operating system and network services.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware offers some unique technological advantages for business and industry.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] For example, traditional database systems are usually deployed in closed environments where users access the system only via a restricted network or intranet (e.g., an enterprise’s internal network).
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] With the phenomenal growth of the World Wide Web, users can access virtually any database for which they have proper access rights from anywhere in the world.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware addresses the problem of varying levels of interoperability among different database structures.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware facilitates transparent access to legacy database management systems (DBMSs) or applications via a web server without regard to database-specific characteristics.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Businesses frequently use middleware applications to link information from departmental databases, such as payroll, sales, and accounting, or databases housed in multiple geographic locations.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] In the highly competitive healthcare community, laboratories make extensive use of middleware applications for data mining, laboratory information system (LIS) backup, and to combine systems during hospital mergers.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware helps bridge the gap between separate LISs in a newly formed healthcare network following a hospital buyout.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Middleware can help software developers avoid having to write application programming interfaces (API) for every control program, by serving as an independent programming interface for their applications.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] For Future Internet network operation through traffic monitoring in multi-domain scenarios, using mediator tools (middleware) is a powerful help since they allow operators, searchers and service providers to supervise Quality of service and analyse eventual failures in telecommunication services.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Finally, e-commerce uses middleware to assist in handling rapid and secure transactions over many different types of computer environments.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] In short, middleware has become a critical element across a broad range of industries, thanks to its ability to bring together resources across dissimilar networks or computing platforms.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] In 2004 members of the European Broadcasting Union (EBU) carried out a study of Middleware with respect to system integration in broadcast environments.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] This involved system design engineering experts from 10 major European broadcasters working over a 12-month period to understand the effect of predominantly software-based products to media production and broadcasting system design techniques.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] The resulting reports Tech 3300 and Tech 3300s were published and are freely available from the EBU web site.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Message-oriented middleware (MOM) is middleware where transactions or event notifications are delivered between disparate systems or components by way of messages, often via an enterprise messaging system.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] With MOM, messages sent to the client are collected and stored until they are acted upon, while the client continues with other processing.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] software may queue, duplicate, translate and deliver messages to disparate systems or components in a messaging system.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Intelligent Middleware (IMW) provides real-time intelligence and event management through intelligent agents.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] The IMW manages the real-time processing of high volume sensor signals and turns these signals into intelligent and actionable business information.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] The actionable information is then delivered in end-user power dashboards to individual users or is pushed to systems within or outside the enterprise.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] It is able to support various heterogeneous types of hardware and software and provides an API for interfacing with external systems.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] It should have a highly scalable, distributed architecture which embeds intelligence throughout the network to transform raw data systematically into actionable and relevant knowledge.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] It can also be packaged with tools to view and manage operations and build advanced network applications most effectively.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Content-centric middleware offers a simple *provider-consumer* abstraction through which applications can issue requests for uniquely identified content, without worrying about where or how it is obtained.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Juno is one example, which allows applications to generate content requests associated with high-level delivery requirements.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] The middleware then adapts the underlying delivery to access the content from sources that are best suited to matching the requirements.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] This is therefore similar to Publish/subscribe middleware, as well as the Content-centric networking paradigm.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware enables a client to use services running on remote systems.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] middleware, it is possible for applications to send objects and request services in an object-oriented system.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] is middleware between applications and database servers.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] integration interface that operates between embedded applications, the embedded operating system, and external applications.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliance is a generic term referring to any form of middleware that manages policy rules.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] They can mediate between data owners or producers, data aggregators, and data users.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Among heterogeneous institutional systems or networks they may be used to enforce, reconcile, and monitor agreed information management policies and laws across systems (or between jurisdictions) with divergent information policies or needs.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Policy appliances support policy-based information management processes by enabling rules-based processing, selective disclosure, and accountability and oversight.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] IBM, Red Hat, Oracle Corporation and Microsoft are some of the vendors that provide middleware software.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Vendors such as Axway, SAP, TIBCO, Informatica, Objective Interface Systems, Pervasive, ScaleOut Software and webMethods were specifically founded to provide more niche middleware solutions.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Groups such as the Apache Software Foundation, OpenSAF, the ObjectWeb Consortium (now OW2) and OASIS' AMQP encourage the development of open source middleware.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Microsoft .NET "Framework" architecture is essentially "Middleware" with typical middleware functions distributed between the various products, with most inter-computer interaction by industry standards, open APIs or RAND software licence.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] Solace provides middleware in purpose-built hardware for implementations that may experience scale.
[src:polka-node/middleware-distributed-applications] StormMQ provides Message Oriented Middleware as a service.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:polka-node/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:polka-node/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:polka-node/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:polka-node/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:polka-node/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:polka-node/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:polka-node/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:polka-node/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:polka-node/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:polka-node/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:polka-node/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:polka-node/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:polka-node/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:polka-node/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:polka-node/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:polka-node/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:polka-node/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:polka-node/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:polka-node/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:polka-node/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:polka-node/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:polka-node/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:polka-node/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:polka-node/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:polka-node/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:polka-node/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:polka-node/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:polka-node/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:polka-node/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:polka-node/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:polka-node/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:polka-node/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:polka-node/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:polka-node/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:polka-node/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:polka-node/routing] In packet switching networks, routing is the higher-level decision-making that directs network packets from their source toward their destination through intermediate network nodes by specific packet forwarding mechanisms.
[src:polka-node/routing] Packet forwarding is the transit of network packets from one network interface to another.
[src:polka-node/routing] Intermediate nodes are typically network hardware devices such as routers, gateways, firewalls, or switches.
[src:polka-node/routing] General-purpose computers also forward packets and perform routing, although they have no specially optimized hardware for the task.
[src:polka-node/routing] The routing process usually directs forwarding on the basis of routing tables.
[src:polka-node/routing] Routing tables maintain a record of the routes to various network destinations.
[src:polka-node/routing] Routing tables may be specified by an administrator, learned by observing network traffic or built with the assistance of routing protocols.
[src:polka-node/routing] Routing, in a narrower sense of the term, often refers to IP routing and is contrasted with bridging.
[src:polka-node/routing] IP routing assumes that network addresses are structured and that similar addresses imply proximity within the network.
[src:polka-node/routing] Structured addresses allow a single routing table entry to represent the route to a group of devices.
[src:polka-node/routing] In large networks, structured addressing (routing, in the narrow sense) outperforms unstructured addressing (bridging).
[src:polka-node/routing] Routing has become the dominant form of addressing on the Internet.
[src:polka-node/routing] Bridging is still widely used within local area networks.
[src:polka-node/routing] Unicast is the dominant form of message delivery on the Internet.
[src:polka-node/routing] This article focuses on unicast routing algorithms.
[src:polka-node/routing] With static routing, small networks may use manually configured routing tables.
[src:polka-node/routing] Larger networks have complex topologies that can change rapidly, making the manual construction of routing tables unfeasible.
[src:polka-node/routing] Nevertheless, most of the public switched telephone network (PSTN) uses pre-computed routing tables, with fallback routes if the most direct route becomes blocked (see routing in the PSTN).
[src:polka-node/routing] Dynamic routing attempts to solve this problem by constructing routing tables automatically, based on information carried by routing protocols, allowing the network to act nearly autonomously in avoiding network failures and blockages.
[src:polka-node/routing] Examples of dynamic-routing protocols and algorithms include Routing Information Protocol (RIP), Open Shortest Path First (OSPF) and Enhanced Interior Gateway Routing Protocol (EIGRP).
[src:polka-node/routing] Distance vector algorithms use the Bellman–Ford algorithm.
[src:polka-node/routing] This approach assigns a *cost* number to each of the links between each node in the network.
[src:polka-node/routing] Nodes send information from point A to point B via the path that results in the lowest *total cost* (i.e., the sum of the costs of the links between the nodes used).
[src:polka-node/routing] When a node first starts, it only knows of its immediate neighbors and the direct cost involved in reaching them.
[src:polka-node/routing] The neighboring nodes examine this information and compare it to what they already know; anything that represents an improvement on what they already have, they insert in their own table.
[src:polka-node/routing] Over time, all the nodes in the network discover the best next hop and total cost for all destinations.
[src:polka-node/routing] When a network node goes down, any nodes that used it as their next hop discard the entry and convey the updated routing information to all adjacent nodes, which in turn repeat the process.
[src:polka-node/routing] Eventually, all the nodes in the network receive the updates and discover new paths to all the destinations that do not involve the down node.
[src:polka-node/routing] When applying link-state algorithms, a graphical map of the network is the fundamental data used for each node.
[src:polka-node/routing] To produce its map, each node floods the entire network with information about the other nodes it can connect to.
[src:polka-node/routing] Each node then independently assembles this information into a map.
[src:polka-node/routing] Using this map, each router independently determines the least-cost path from itself to every other node using a standard shortest paths algorithm such as Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:polka-node/routing] The result is a tree graph rooted at the current node, such that the path through the tree from the root to any other node is the least-cost path to that node.
[src:polka-node/routing] This tree then serves to construct the routing table, which specifies the best next hop to get from the current node to any other node.
[src:polka-node/routing] A link-state routing algorithm optimized for mobile ad hoc networks is the optimized Link State Routing Protocol (OLSR).
[src:polka-node/routing] OLSR is proactive; it uses Hello and Topology Control (TC) messages to discover and disseminate link-state information through the mobile ad hoc network.
[src:polka-node/routing] Using Hello messages, each node discovers 2-hop neighbor information and elects a set of *multipoint relays* (MPRs).
[src:polka-node/routing] MPRs distinguish OLSR from other link-state routing protocols.
[src:polka-node/routing] Distance vector and link-state routing are both intra-domain routing protocols.
[src:polka-node/routing] They are used inside an autonomous system, but not between autonomous systems.
[src:polka-node/routing] Both of these routing protocols become intractable in large networks and cannot be used in inter-domain routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] Distance vector routing is subject to instability if there are more than a few hops in the domain.
[src:polka-node/routing] Link-state routing needs significant resources to calculate routing tables.
[src:polka-node/routing] It also creates heavy traffic due to flooding.
[src:polka-node/routing] Path-vector routing is used for inter-domain routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] It is similar to distance vector routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] Path-vector routing assumes that one node (there can be many) in each autonomous system acts on behalf of the entire autonomous system.
[src:polka-node/routing] This node is called the *speaker node.* The speaker node creates a routing table and advertises it to neighboring speaker nodes in neighboring autonomous systems.
[src:polka-node/routing] The idea is the same as distance vector routing, except that only speaker nodes in each autonomous system can communicate with each other.
[src:polka-node/routing] The speaker node advertises the path, not the metric, of the nodes in its autonomous system or other autonomous systems.
[src:polka-node/routing] The path-vector routing algorithm is similar to the distance vector algorithm in the sense that each border router advertises the destinations it can reach to its neighboring router.
[src:polka-node/routing] However, instead of advertising networks in terms of a destination and the distance to that destination, networks are advertised as destination addresses and path descriptions to reach those destinations.
[src:polka-node/routing] The path, expressed in terms of the domains (or confederations) traversed so far, is carried in a special path attribute that records the sequence of routing domains through which the reachability information has passed.
[src:polka-node/routing] A route is defined as a pairing between a destination and the attributes of the path to that destination, thus the name, path-vector routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] The routers receive a vector that contains paths to a set of destinations.
[src:polka-node/routing] Path selection involves applying a routing metric to multiple routes to select (or predict) the best route.
[src:polka-node/routing] Most routing algorithms use only one network path at a time.
[src:polka-node/routing] Multipath routing and specifically equal-cost multi-path routing techniques enable the use of multiple alternative paths.
[src:polka-node/routing] In computer networking, the metric is computed by a routing algorithm, and can cover information such as bandwidth, network delay, hop count, path cost, load, maximum transmission unit, reliability, and communication cost.
[src:polka-node/routing] The routing table stores only the best possible routes, while link-state or topological databases may store all other information as well.
[src:polka-node/routing] *Metric*: When comparing routes learned via the same routing protocol, a lower metric is preferred.
[src:polka-node/routing] Metrics cannot be compared between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:polka-node/routing] *Administrative distance*: When comparing route table entries from different sources, such as different routing protocols and static configuration, a lower administrative distance indicates a more reliable source and thus a preferred route.
[src:polka-node/routing] Because a routing metric is specific to a given routing protocol, multi-protocol routers must use some external heuristic to select between routes learned from different routing protocols.
[src:polka-node/routing] Cisco routers, for example, attribute a value known as the administrative distance to each route, where smaller administrative distances indicate routes learned from a protocol assumed to be more reliable.
[src:polka-node/routing] A local administrator can set up host-specific routes that provide more control over network usage, permit testing, and better overall security.
[src:polka-node/routing] This is useful for debugging network connections or routing tables.
[src:polka-node/routing] In some small systems, a single central device decides ahead of time the complete path of every packet.
[src:polka-node/routing] In some other small systems, whichever edge device injects a packet into the network decides ahead of time the complete path of that particular packet.
[src:polka-node/routing] In either case, the route-planning device needs to know a lot of information about what devices are connected to the network and how they are connected to each other.
[src:polka-node/routing] Once it has this information, it can use an algorithm such as A* search algorithm to find the best path.
[src:polka-node/routing] In high-speed systems, there are so many packets transmitted every second that it is infeasible for a single device to calculate the complete path for each and every packet.
[src:polka-node/routing] Early high-speed systems dealt with this with circuit switching by setting up a path once for the first packet between some source and some destination; later packets between that same source and that same destination continue to follow the same path without recalculating until the circuit teardown.
[src:polka-node/routing] Later high-speed systems inject packets into the network without any one device ever calculating a complete path for packets.
[src:polka-node/routing] In large systems, there are so many connections between devices, and those connections change so frequently, that it is infeasible for any one device to even know how all the devices are connected to each other, much less calculate a complete path through them.
[src:polka-node/routing] Such systems generally use next-hop routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] Most systems use a deterministic dynamic routing algorithm.
[src:polka-node/routing] When a device chooses a path to a particular final destination, that device always chooses the same path to that destination until it receives information that makes it think some other path is better.
[src:polka-node/routing] A few routing algorithms do not use a deterministic algorithm to find the best link for a packet to get from its original source to its final destination.
[src:polka-node/routing] Instead, to avoid congestion hot spots in packet systems, a few algorithms use a randomized algorithm—Valiant's paradigm—that routes a path to a randomly picked intermediate destination, and from there to its true final destination.
[src:polka-node/routing] In many early telephone switches, a randomizer was often used to select the start of a path through a multistage switching fabric.
[src:polka-node/routing] Depending on the application for which path selection is performed, different metrics can be used.
[src:polka-node/routing] For example, for web requests, one can use minimum latency paths to minimize web page load time, or for bulk data transfers, one can choose the least utilized path to balance load across the network and increase throughput.
[src:polka-node/routing] A popular path selection objective is to reduce the average completion times of traffic flows and the total network bandwidth consumption.
[src:polka-node/routing] Recently, a path selection metric was proposed that computes the total number of bytes scheduled on the edges per path as a selection metric.
[src:polka-node/routing] An empirical analysis of several path selection metrics, including this new proposal, has been made available.
[src:polka-node/routing] In some networks, routing is complicated by the fact that no single entity is responsible for selecting paths; instead, multiple entities are involved in selecting paths or even parts of a single path.
[src:polka-node/routing] Complications or inefficiency can result if these entities choose paths to optimize their own objectives, which may conflict with the objectives of other participants.
[src:polka-node/routing] A classic example involves traffic in a road system, in which each driver picks a path that minimizes their travel time.
[src:polka-node/routing] With such routing, the equilibrium routes can be longer than optimal for all drivers.
[src:polka-node/routing] In particular, Braess's paradox shows that adding a new road can *lengthen* travel times for all drivers.
[src:polka-node/routing] In a single-agent model used, for example, for routing automated guided vehicles (AGVs) on a terminal, reservations are made for each vehicle to prevent simultaneous use of the same part of an infrastructure.
[src:polka-node/routing] This approach is also referred to as context-aware routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] The Internet is partitioned into autonomous systems (ASs) such as internet service providers (ISPs), each of which controls routes involving its network.
[src:polka-node/routing] First, AS-level paths are selected via the BGP protocol that produces a sequence of ASs through which packets flow.
[src:polka-node/routing] Each AS may have multiple paths, offered by neighboring ASs, from which to choose.
[src:polka-node/routing] These routing decisions often correlate with business relationships with these neighboring ASs, which may be unrelated to path quality or latency.
[src:polka-node/routing] Second, once an AS-level path has been selected, there are often multiple corresponding router-level paths to choose from.
[src:polka-node/routing] This is due, in part, because two ISPs may be connected through multiple connections.
[src:polka-node/routing] In choosing the single router-level path, it is common practice for each ISP to employ hot-potato routing: sending traffic along the path that minimizes the distance through the ISP's own network—even if that path lengthens the total distance to the destination.
[src:polka-node/routing] For example, consider two ISPs, *A* and *B*.
[src:polka-node/routing] Each has a presence in New York, connected by a fast link with latency 5 ms—and each has a presence in London connected by a 5 ms link.
[src:polka-node/routing] Suppose both ISPs have trans-Atlantic links that connect their two networks, but *A*'s link has latency 100 ms and *B*'s has latency 120 ms.
[src:polka-node/routing] When routing a message from a source in *A*'s London network to a destination in *B*'s New York network, *A* may choose to immediately send the message to *B* in London.
[src:polka-node/routing] This saves *A* the work of sending it along an expensive trans-Atlantic link, but causes the message to experience latency 125 ms when the other route would have been 20 ms faster.
[src:polka-node/routing] Additionally, a similar routing challenge can be observed in cellular networks, where different packets are destined for various endpoints, and each link exhibits varying spectral efficiency.
[src:polka-node/routing] In this context, the selection of the *optimal* path involves considering latency and packet error rate.
[src:polka-node/routing] To address this, multiple independent entities, one for each base station, play a crucial role in path selection while striving to optimize overall network performance.
[src:polka-node/routing] A 2003 measurement study of Internet routes found that, between pairs of neighboring ISPs, more than 30% of paths have inflated latency due to hot-potato routing, with 5% of paths being delayed by at least 12 ms.
[src:polka-node/routing] Inflation due to AS-level path selection, while substantial, was attributed primarily to BGP's lack of a mechanism to directly optimize for latency, rather than to selfish routing policies.
[src:polka-node/routing] It was also suggested that, were an appropriate mechanism in place, ISPs would be willing to cooperate to reduce latency rather than use hot-potato routing.
[src:polka-node/routing] Such a mechanism was later published by the same authors, first for the case of two ISPs and then for the global case.
[src:polka-node/routing] As the Internet and IP networks have become mission critical business tools, there has been increased interest in techniques and methods to monitor the routing posture of networks.
[src:polka-node/routing] Incorrect routing or routing issues cause undesirable performance degradation, flapping or downtime.
[src:polka-node/routing] Monitoring routing in a network is achieved using route analytics tools and techniques.
[src:polka-node/routing] In networks where a logically centralized control is available over the forwarding state, for example, using software-defined networking, routing techniques can be used that aim to optimize global and network-wide performance metrics.
[src:polka-node/routing] This has been used by large internet companies that operate many data centers in different geographical locations attached using private optical links, examples of which include Microsoft's Global WAN, Facebook's Express Backbone, and Google's B4.
[src:polka-node/routing] Global performance metrics to optimize include maximizing network utilization, minimizing traffic flow completion times, maximizing the traffic delivered prior to specific deadlines and reducing the completion times of flows.
[src:polka-node/routing] Work on the later over private WAN discusses modeling routing as a graph optimization problem by pushing all the queuing to the end-points.
[src:polka-node/routing] The authors also propose a heuristic to solve the problem efficiently while sacrificing negligible performance.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A **web server** is computer software that accepts requests via HTTP (the network protocol created to distribute web content) or its secure variant HTTPS.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A user agent, commonly a web browser or web crawler, initiates communication by making a request for a web page or other resource using HTTP, and the server responds with the content of that resource or an error message.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A web server can also accept and store resources sent from the user agent if configured to do so.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The hardware used to run a web server can vary according to the volume of requests that it needs to handle.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] At the low end of the range are embedded systems, such as a router that runs a small web server as its configuration interface.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A high-traffic Internet website might handle requests with hundreds of servers that run on racks of high-speed computers.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A resource sent from a web server can be a pre-existing file (static content) available to the web server, or it can be generated at the time of the request (dynamic content) by another program that communicates with the server software.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The former usually can be served faster and can be more easily cached for repeated requests, while the latter supports a broader range of applications.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Technologies such as REST and SOAP, which use HTTP as a basis for general computer-to-computer communication, as well as support for WebDAV extensions, have extended the application of web servers well beyond their original purpose of serving human-readable pages.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In March 1989, Sir Tim Berners-Lee proposed a new project to his employer CERN, with the goal of easing the exchange of information between scientists by using a hypertext system.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The proposal titled *"HyperText and CERN"*, asked for comments and it was read by several people.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In October 1990 the proposal was reformulated and enriched (having as co-author Robert Cailliau), and finally, it was approved.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Those early browsers retrieved web pages written in a simple early form of HTML from web servers using a new basic communication protocol that was named HTTP 0.9.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In August 1991 Tim Berners-Lee announced the *birth of WWW technology* and encouraged scientists to adopt and develop it.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Soon after, those programs, along with their source code, were made available to people interested in their usage.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Although the source code was not formally licensed or placed in the public domain, CERN informally allowed users and developers to experiment and further develop on top of them.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Berners-Lee started promoting the adoption and the usage of those programs along with their porting to other operating systems.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In December 1991, the **first web server outside Europe** was installed at SLAC (U.S.A.).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] This was a very important event because it started trans-continental web communications between web browsers and web servers.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In 1991–1993, CERN web server program continued to be actively developed by the www group, meanwhile, thanks to the availability of its source code and the public specifications of the HTTP protocol, many other implementations of web servers started to be developed.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In April 1993, CERN issued a public official statement stating that the three components of Web software (the basic line-mode client, the web server and the library of common code), along with their source code, were put in the public domain.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] This statement freed web server developers from any possible legal issue about the development of *derivative work* based on that source code (a threat that in practice never existed).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1994, the most notable among new web servers was NCSA httpd which ran on a variety of Unix-based OSs and could serve *dynamically generated content* by implementing the `POST` HTTP method and the CGI to communicate with external programs.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] These capabilities, along with the multimedia features of NCSA's Mosaic browser (also able to manage HTML FORMs in order to send data to a web server) highlighted the potential of web technology for publishing and distributed computing applications.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] At the beginning of 1995 those patches were all applied to the last release of NCSA source code and, after several tests, the Apache HTTP server project was started.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] At the end of 1994, a new commercial web server, named Netsite, was released with specific features.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] It was the first one of many other similar products that were developed first by Netscape, then also by Sun Microsystems, and finally by Oracle Corporation.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In mid-1995, the first version of IIS was released by Microsoft for Windows NT OS.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] This marked the entry, in the field of World Wide Web technologies, of a commercial developer and vendor that has played and still is playing a key role on both sides (client and server) of the web.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In the second half of 1995, CERN and NCSA web servers started to decline (in global percentage usage) because of the widespread adoption of new web servers which had a much faster development cycle along with more features, more fixes applied, and more performances than the previous ones.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] At the end of 1996, there were already over fifty known, different web-server-software programs that were available to everybody who wanted to own an Internet domain name or to host websites.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Many of them lived only shortly and were replaced by other web servers.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The publication of RFCs about protocol versions HTTP/1.0 (1996) and HTTP/1.1 (1997, 1999), forced most web servers to comply (not always completely) with those standards.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The use of TCP/IP persistent connections (HTTP/1.1) required web servers both to increase the maximum number of concurrent connections allowed and to improve their level of scalability.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Between 1996 and 1999, Netscape Enterprise Server and Microsoft's IIS emerged among the leading commercial options whereas among the freely available and open-source programs Apache HTTP Server held the lead as the preferred server (because of its reliability and its many features).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In those years there was also another commercial web server called Zeus (*now discontinued*) that was known as one of the fastest and most scalable web servers available on market, at least till the first decade of 2000s, despite its low percentage of usage.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Apache resulted in the most used web server from mid-1996 to the end of 2015 when, after a few years of decline, it was surpassed initially by IIS and then by Nginx.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Afterward IIS dropped to much lower percentages of usage than Apache (see also market share).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] From 2005–2006, Apache started to improve its speed and its scalability level by introducing new performance features (e.g., event MPM and new content cache).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A few years after 2000 started, not only other commercial and highly competitive web servers (e.g., LiteSpeed) but also many other open-source programs such as Hiawatha, Cherokee HTTP server, Lighttpd, Nginx and other derived and related products also available with commercial support emerged.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Within a year, these changes, on average, nearly tripled the maximum number of persistent connections that web servers had to manage.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In 2015, RFCs published new protocol version [HTTP/2], and as the implementation of new specifications was not trivial at all, a **dilemma arose among developers of less popular web servers** (e.g., with a percentage of usage lower than 1% ..
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] 2%), about adding or not adding support for that new protocol version.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In 2020–2021 the HTTP/2 dynamics about its implementation (by top web servers and popular web browsers) were partly replicated after the publication of advanced drafts of future RFC about HTTP/3 protocol.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The following technical overview should be considered only as an attempt to give a few very *limited examples* about *some* features that may be implemented in a web server and *some* of the tasks that it may perform in order to have a sufficiently wide scenario about the topic.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A **web server program** plays the role of a server in a client–server model by implementing one or more versions of HTTP protocol, often including the HTTPS secure variant and other features and extensions that are considered useful for its planned usage.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Although web server programs differ in how they are implemented, most of them offer the following common features.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] These are **basic features** that most web servers usually have.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A few other more **advanced** and popular **features** (*only a very short selection*) are the following ones.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Once an HTTP request message has been decoded and verified, its values can be used to determine whether that request can be satisfied or not.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] This requires many other steps, including **security checks**.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The term *URL normalization* refers to the process of modifying and standardizing a URL in a consistent manner.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] There are several types of normalization that may be performed, including the conversion of the scheme and host to lowercase.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Among the most important normalizations are the removal of "." and ".." path segments and adding trailing slashes to a non-empty path component.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] One or more configuration files of web server may specify the mapping of parts of **URL path** (e.g., initial parts of file path, filename extension and other path components) to a specific URL handler (file, directory, external program or internal module).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to translate an URL path (all or part of it), that refers to a physical file system path, to an absolute path under the target website's root directory.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Website's root directory may be specified by a configuration file or by some internal rule of the web server by using the name of the website which is the host part of the URL found in HTTP client request.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The web server appends the path found in requested URL (HTTP request message) and appends it to the path of the (Host) website root directory.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] On an Apache server, this is commonly `/home/www/website` (on Unix machines, usually it is: `/var/www/website`).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] See the following examples of how it may result.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The web server then reads the file, if it exists, and sends a response to the client's web browser.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the file and contain the file itself or an error message will return saying that the file does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The response will describe the content of the directory (list of contained subdirectories and files) or an error message will return saying that the directory does not exist or its access is forbidden.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] For a *dynamic request* the URL path specified by the client should refer to an existing external program (usually an executable file with a CGI) used by the web server to generate dynamic content.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The web server executes that program, passing in the path-info and the query string `action=view&orderby=thread&date=2021-10-15` so that the program has the info it needs to run.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] (In this case, it will return an HTML document containing a view of forum entries ordered by thread from October 15, 2021).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In addition to this, the web server reads data sent from the external program and resends that data to the client that made the request.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Once a request has been read, interpreted, and verified, it has to be managed depending on its method, its URL, and its parameters, which may include values of HTTP headers.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] That kind of content is called *static* because usually it is not changed by the web server when it is sent to clients and because it remains the same until it is modified (file modification) by some program.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Response of static file content can be sped up by a **file cache**.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Most used names for static index files are: `index.html`, `index.htm` and `Default.htm`.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] If a web server program receives a client request message with an URL whose path matches the file name of an existing *file* and that file is accessible by web server program and its attributes match internal rules of web server program, then web server program can send that file to client.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Usually, for security reasons, most web server programs are pre-configured to serve only regular files or to avoid to use *special file types* like device files, along with symbolic links or hard links to them.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The aim is to avoid undesirable side effects when serving static web resources.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] If a web server program is capable of **serving dynamic content** and it has been configured to do so, then it is able to communicate with the proper internal module or external program (associated with the requested URL path) in order to pass to it the parameters of the client request.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] After that, the web server program reads from it its data response (that it has generated, often on the fly) and then it resends it to the client program who made the request.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In order to be able to communicate with its internal modules or external programs, a web server program must have implemented one or more of the many available **gateway interfaces** (see also Web Server Gateway Interfaces used for dynamic content).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The three **standard** and historical **gateway interfaces** are the following ones.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] An external CGI program is run by web server program for each dynamic request, then web server program reads from it the generated data response and then resends it to client.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] An external FastCGI program (it usually is a process) is started once by web server program or by some other program or process and then it waits for a network connection which is established permanently by web server; through that connection are sent the request parameters and read data responses.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A web server program may be capable to manage the dynamic generation (on the fly) of a **directory index list** of files and sub-directories.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] If it cannot be generated an error is returned.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Usage of dynamically generated *directory listings* is usually avoided or limited to a few selected directories of a website because that generation takes much more OS resources than sending a static index page.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The main usage of *directory listings* is to allow the download of files (usually when their names, sizes, modification date-times or file attributes may change randomly and frequently) *as they are, without requiring to provide further information to requesting user*.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In practice whenever there is content that may vary, depending on one or more parameters contained in client request or in configuration settings, then, usually, it is generated dynamically.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Web server programs are able to send response messages as replies to client request messages.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] An error response message may be sent because a request message could not be successfully read or decoded or analyzed or executed.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] NOTE: the following sections are reported only as examples to help to understand what a web server, more or less, does; these sections are by any means neither exhaustive nor complete.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] When an error response or message is received by a client browser, then if it is related to the main user request (e.g., an URL of a web resource such as a web page) then usually that error message is shown in some browser window or message.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Example 1: a URL path points to a **directory** name but it does not have a final slash '/' so web server sends a redirect to client in order to instruct it to redo the request with the fixed path name.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Example 2: a whole set of documents has been **moved inside website** in order to reorganize their file system paths.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Example 3: a whole set of documents has been **moved to a new website** and now it is mandatory to use secure HTTPS connections to access them.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Above examples are only a few of the possible kind of redirections.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A web server program is able to reply to a valid client request message with a successful message, optionally containing requested **web resource data**.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] If web resource data is sent back to client, then it can be **static content** or **dynamic content** depending on how it has been retrieved (from a file or from the output of some program or module).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In order to speed up web server responses by lowering average HTTP response times and hardware resources used, many popular web servers implement one or more content caches, each one specialized in a content category.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In practice, nowadays, many web server programs include their own *userland* **file cache**, tailored for a web server usage and using their specific implementation and parameters.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] The wide spread adoption of RAID and fast solid-state drives (storage hardware with very high I/O speed) has slightly reduced but of course not eliminated the advantage of having a file cache incorporated in a web server.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Dynamic content, output by an internal module or an external program, may not always change very frequently (given a unique URL with keys or parameters) and so, maybe for a while (e.g., from one second to several hours or more), the resulting output can be cached in RAM or even on a fast disk.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Anyway, in most cases those kind of caches are implemented by external servers (e.g., reverse proxy) or by storing dynamic data output in separate computers, managed by specific applications (e.g., memcached), in order to not compete for hardware resources (CPU, RAM, disks) with web servers.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] A web server software can be either incorporated into the OS and executed in kernel space, or it can be executed in user space (like other regular applications).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Web servers that run in user-mode have to ask the system for permission to use more memory or more CPU resources.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Not only do these requests to the kernel take time, but they might not always be satisfied because the system reserves resources for its own usage and has the responsibility to share hardware resources with all the other running applications.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Executing in user mode can also mean using more buffer or data copies (between user-space and kernel-space) which can lead to a decrease in the performance of a user-mode web server.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Nowadays almost all web server software is executed in user mode (because many of the aforementioned small disadvantages have been overcome by faster hardware, new OS versions, much faster OS system calls and new optimized web server software).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] See also comparison of web server software to discover which of them run in kernel mode or in user mode (also referred as kernel space or user space).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In other words, a **web server should always be very responsive**, even under high load of web traffic, in order to keep **total user's wait** (sum of browser time + network time + **web server response time**) for a response **as low as possible**.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Among the operating conditions, the **number** (1 ..
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] *n*) of **concurrent client connections** used during a test is an important parameter because it allows to correlate the **concurrency level** supported by web server with results of the tested performance metrics.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] ... used to implement a web server program, **can bias a lot the performances** and in particular the **scalability level** that can be achieved under **heavy load** or when using high end hardware (many CPUs, disks and lots of RAM).
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] In practice some web server software models may require more OS resources (specially more CPUs and more RAM) than others to be able to work well and so to achieve target performances.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p01] Performances of a web server are typically benchmarked by using one or more of the available automated load testing tools.
[src:polka-node/web-server-p02] When a web server is near to or over its load limits, it gets **overloaded** and so it may become **unresponsive**.
